data.shownotes: Cellophane contained I'm In Your Mind and I'm Not In Your Mind teases. Am I In Heaven? was played for the first time since 2016-05-14. (70 show gap) KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete. Billabong Valley and Rattlesnake were confirmed by audio/video recordings. The remaining songs were confirmed through the written setlist and contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlist@kglw.net.

KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete. All songs aside from Anoxia, Invisible Face and Gamma Knife through Am I In Heaven? were confirmed by audio/video recordings. The remaining songs were confirmed through contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlist@kglw.net.

All Is Known was introduced as a new song and contained alternate lyrics. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete. Open Water through Rattlesnake were confirmed by the band's Facebook livestream and the Altered Beast suite was confirmed by audio/video recordings. The remaining songs were confirmed through contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlist@kglw.net.

Crosstown Traffic (The Jimi Hendrix Experience) played before and as the band walked on stage for the second set. The Altered Beast suite and The Balrog were introduced as new songs. Before Alter Me I, the band took a moment to fix loud buzzing coming from Ambrose's equipment. Invisible Face was incomplete. Am I In Heaven? contained Alter Me and Cellophane teases and quotes, Rattlesnake, Hot Water, and Head On/Pill teases, and a Sea Of Trees jam with lyrics. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete. Alter Me I through Am I In Heaven? were confirmed by the band's Facebook livestream. The remaining songs were confirmed through contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlist@kglw.net.

High Voltage (AC/DC) played before and as the band walked on stage for the first set. All Is Known was introduced as a new song and contained alternate lyrics. During Billabong Valley, the guitar strap fell off the Flying Microtonal Banana while Ambrose was using it, with Joey jokingly telling Stu afterwards that his guitar was broken and that Ambrose should "stick to the blues harp". NOBODY'S BABY (Sheer Mag) played before and as the band walked on stage for the second set. Before Gamma Knife, the crowd started chanting for Stu to do a "shoey", to which he told them to "be reasonable" and that he was "too old for that". The Balrog was introduced as a new song. Am I In Heaven? contained a medley of teases and quotes including Alter Me, Cellophane, Rattlesnake, Hot Water, Head On/Pill and The River as well as a Sea of Trees jam with lyrics. This performance was filmed in 360-degree video and released as "King Gizzard & The Lizard Wizard - 360° Full Concert" on the Banalarama YouTube channel, featuring audio mixed by Stu
Webcast live by Pitchfork. Night one was performed in the grand ballroom.
Sea Of Trees was played for the first time known since 2014-10-24. (217 show gap)

This show featured the debut of Vomit Coffin. Following Rattlesnake, the band wished a happy birthday to Eric. Am I In Heaven? contained teases and quotes of Cellophane, The River, Head On/Pill, I'm In Your Mind, Sea of Trees, Rattlesnake, and Robot Stop. Prior to the show, Stu accidentally posted a link containing demos for all of Polygondwanaland to the Facebook fan page under the name “Blinky Bill”. Although removed shortly after, someone was able to download the first two demos causing Stu to message them claiming he was a fan named Han-Tyumi and asked for the demos not to be reposted. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete, but no recordings are available. KGLW.net staff believes the setlist is complete based on contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlist@kglw.net.

This was an in-studio appearance for radio station KEXP in Seattle. Following the performance Stu had a 5 minute interview with KEXP DJ Cheryl Waters.

data.showtitle: Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival

data.shownotes: During final song Stu crowd surfed out of the venue and into the sea, while the band continued to play.
Poster by Olya Dyer, limited to 100

This show featured the debuts of Some Context, Welcome to an Altered Future, Digital Black, and Han-Tyumi, The Confused Cyborg. Billabong Valley was dedicated to Charles Bradley, who had passed that day. Lonely Steel Sheet Flyer was played for the first time known since 2015-09-11. (174 show gap) Robot Stop contained a Master Of The Universe' jam with lyrics.

Members of Mild High Club joined the band for Countdown and Rolling Stoned. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist is believed to be complete. Rattlesnake, Countdown and Rolling Stoned were confirmed by audio/video recordings. The remaining songs were confirmed via contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net.

The first performance of Rolling Stoned was played as the last song of Mild High Club's set, with the members of King Gizzard joining in mid-song. Robot Stop contained a Master of the Universe jam with lyrics. Members of Mild High Club joined the band for Countdown and the second performance of Rolling Stoned. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist is believed to be complete. Sleep Drifter, Rattlesnake, Lonely Steel Sheet Flyer, Robot Stop through Gamma Knife, Countdown and both performances of Rolling Stoned were confirmed by audio/video recordings. The remaining songs were confirmed via contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net.
The band walked out to Let There Be Rock by AC/DC.
Robot Stop contained a Master Of The Universe jam with lyrics.
Am I In Heaven? contained People Vultures, Cut Throat Boogie, Rattlesnake, Alter Me, Robot Stop, Cellophane, I'm In Your Mind, Head On/Pill, and Float Along - Fill Your Lungs teases and quotes.

This show featured the debuts of Greenhouse Heat Death, D-Day, The Book, Polygondwanaland, and The Fourth Colour. The vocal intro to Nuclear Fusion was not performed. All Is Known was played for the first time since 2018-02-18. (69 show gap) Doom City contained a Crumbling Castle outro. Evil Death Roll was played for the first time since 2017-06-06. (50 show gap) Big Fig Wasp was played for the first time since 2016-09-22. (100 show gap)

The Coffee Cola Song (Francis Bebey) played as the band came on stage. At the start of the show, Joey says this is "the biggest show we've ever played". Before Nuclear Fusion, Joey said that he had said he wasn't going to do the vocal intro anymore, but that he'd "do it tonight". He jokingly apologized to Sam after the vocal intro. The Book was instrumental. Doom City contained a Crumbling Castle outro. Sister Ray (The Velvet Underground) was played over the PA as the setbreak music with a 15 minute countdown on the screen. Han-Tyumi, The Confused Cyborg contained alternate lyrics and Stu on flute. Robot Stop contained a Hot Water tease.

Poster by Olya Dyer limited to 100 prints KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete. Big Fig Wasp was confirmed through video recording. The rest of the songs were confirmed via contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net.

“Electricity” (Captain Beefheart) played from the PA as the band came on stage. Doom City contained a Crumbling Castle outro. Han-Tyumi, The Confused Cyborg featured Stu on flute and alternate lyrics same as the KEXP performance. During the jam before Robot Stop, which contained The River, Am I In Heaven?, and Head On/Pill teases and quotes, Stu shouted out visual artist Jason Galea and wished him a happy birthday. Robot Stop contained a “Master Of The Universe” (Hawkwind) jam with lyrics. Poster by Carlo Vivary
Vomit Coffin was played for the first time since 2017-04-12. (82 show gap) Altered Beast I was played for the first time since 2017-04-18. (78 show gap)

Riff Raff (AC/DC) played as the band came on stage. Before Digital Black, Joey said "this is our biggest show in America, ever", and Stu thanked Amyl & The Sniffers (the opening act). Vomit Coffin was incomplete. Alter Me I was incomplete. Before Rattlesnake, Stu shouted out John Bonham as a "s--t bloke, good drummer", followed by a short Moby Dick (Led Zeppelin) tease. The vocal intro to Nuclear Fusion was not performed. Before The Wheel Joey shouted out Sammy on the sound, Jason Galea who was working the projectors, Gaspard who was working the monitors, and "Nate Dog on the merch". Robot Stop contained Hot Water teases, and the intro contained a Trapdoor tease. Joey thanked Amyl & The Sniffers again after Gamma Knife.

“Whiplash” (Metallica) played as the band came on stage. Vomit Coffin and Alter Me I were incomplete. Before Rattlesnake, Stu shouted out Amyl & The Sniffers, the opening act. Greenhouse Heat Death contained a Sleep Drifter tease. Sleep Drifter contained a Rattlesnake tease. Billabong Valley contained a Sleep Drifter tease. After The Wheel, Joey said "That song was our Jerry Garcia attempt". The intro to Robot Stop contained Trapdoor, Cellophane, and Hot Water teases, and the song itself contained a Hot Water tease. At the end of the show, Joey shouted out the Golden State Warriors, the local NBA team, who were in the midst of the 2018 NBA finals series.

Head On/Pill was played for the first time since 2017-06-24. (68 show gap). The intro to Robot Stop contained Trapdoor and Hot Water teases. Head On/Pill contained Sea of Trees teases and quotes, Hot Water teases, Alter Me I teases and quotes, Am I In Heaven? teases and quotes, a Robot Stop tease, and Cellophane teases and quotes.

The intro to Robot Stop contained Cellophane and Head On/Pill teases. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete, but only partial recordings are available. Robot Stop through Big Fig Wasp, Rattlesnake, All Is Known through Digital Black and The Lord of Lightning through Crumbling Castle have been confirmed via audio/video recordings. The remaining songs were confirmed by contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net.
Altered Beast II was played for the first time since 2017-10-14. (53 show gap)

Before Digital Black, Stu asked the crowd if anyone was at the band's previous show in Atlanta, followed by Cavs briefly teasing Moby Dick. Hot Wax, which was played for the first time known since 2016-05-14 (199 show gap), was performed at the request of a fan who asked the band after their previous show if they could play it. Billabong Valley was dedicated to "all them abandoned kitties next door". Sleep Drifter contained a Honey intro tease. After All Is Known, Joey shouted out an audience member's 21st birthday and brought them on stage. Only Part I of The River was played, and it contained a brief blues intro. Wah Wah was played for the first time since 2016-12-09 (138 show gap) and contained The River quotes and teases. Robot Stop contained a “Master Of The Universe” (Hawkwind) jam with lyrics and Hot Water teases.

This show opened with an extended jam before the band's set that evolved out of the band tuning, which contained Head On/Pill teases. Am I In Heaven? was played for the first time since 2017-10-07. (81 show gap) KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist may be incomplete and out of order. Rattlesnake was confirmed via audio/video recording and the opening jam was confirmed by audio/video from THE NONAGON MOVIE, which includes dates and venue for each clip in the video description. The remaining songs were confirmed via the physical written setlist and contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net.

Planet B and portions of Self-Immolate and Organ Farmer were released on the PHC FILMS YouTube channel. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete, but only partial recordings are available. Self-Immolate, Planet B, Gamma Knife through Billabong Valley, Cyboogie through Murder Of The Universe and Organ Farmer have been confirmed via audio/video recordings. The remaining songs were confirmed via the physical written setlist and contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net. Poster By Jason Galea Edition of 100

KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete, but only partial recordings are available. Billabong Valley was confirmed via audio/video recordings. The remaining songs were confirmed via the physical written setlist and contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net. Poster By Jason Galea Edition of 100

This show featured the debut of Real's Not Real. Evil Star was played through the PA speakers before and as the band came on stage. Hot Water was played for the first time since 2017-10-12 (104 show gap) and featured Adam Halliwell (introduced as the band's best friend) on flute. Following Open Water, which featured a drum solo, Joey pretended to be introducing John Henry Bonham playing Moby Dick. Loyalty featured use of a vocoder for Joey's vocals and Stu on flute. After Horology, Joey thanked openers C.O.F.F.I.N, Bitch Diesel, and "our sexy young lad friends Mildlife". Head On/Pill featured Adam Halliwell on flute, Hot Water, Alter Me. Cellophane, I'm In Your Mind, and Am I In Heaven? teases and quotes, and Robot Stop, Cyboogie, Horology, Organ Farmer, and Rattlesnake teases. This show was released through the Official Bootlegger program as Live in Adelaide ‘19. Poster By Jason Galea Edition of 100

This show took place at the former Fillmore West space. Evil Star was played through the PA speakers before and as the band came on stage. Joey shouted out The Grateful Dead before Mars For the Rich. I'm Not In Your Mind and I'm In Your Mind Fuzz contained Altered Beast teases. Cellophane contained Alter Me quotes and teases. This Thing was introduced by Joey as a "song about communism." Billabong Valley was introduced by Ambrose as a “song about a bush ranger buddy.” Joey thanked ORB and Stonefield before Perihelion.

data.showtitle: Infest the Rat's Nest Album Release Show
data.shownotes:
“Infest the Rats’ Nest” album was released the day of the show. Evil Star was played through the PA speakers before and as the band went on stage. Open Water featured a drum solo. Am I In Heaven? contained Alter Me, Robot Stop and Cellophane teases and quotes and Rattlesnake and Big Fig Wasp teases.

Poster By Jason Galea
Edition of 100

Evil Star was played through the PA speakers before and as the band came on stage. After Horology, there was a brief pause to fix Ambrose's microphone, in which Joey calls out "Somebody get this shrimp a microphone!". I'm Not In Your Mind contained a Cellophane tease. Before Boogieman Sam, 'Freak' (Silverchair) was teased.


Poster By Jason Galea
Edition of 100

Evil Star was played through the PA speakers as the band went on stage. Only Part I of The River was performed and it contained Wah Wah teases. Wah Wah contained The River quotes. During The Cruel Millennial and The Wheel, Ambrose wore an audience member's fishie helmet. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist is believed to be complete. Planet B and Plastic Boogie through Self-Immolate were confirmed by audio/video recordings. The remaining songs were confirmed via the written setlist and contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net. Poster By Jason Galea Edition of 100

Evil Star was played through the PA speakers before the band as came on stage. Stu and Joey introduced Gaspard, their sound tech, after Murder of the Universe. The band shouted out their sound tech Sammy before Boogieman Sam. Joey thanked openers Stonefield and ORB before Self-Immolate. Sense was on the written setlist after The Bird Song but was replaced with Let Me Mend The Past.

Poster By Jason Galea
Edition of 100

Evil Star was played through the PA speakers before the band as came on stage. Mr. Beat was played for the first time since 2016-09-22. (215 show gap) The Han-Tyumi voice said "Thank You" after Evil Death Roll, after Murder of the Universe, and after Altered Beast II. Only one verse of Alter Me I was sung. Mars For the Rich is included in the Chunky Shrapnel Special Features.

Poster By Jason Galea
Edition of 200

The River contained Wah Wah teases and quotes. Am I in Heaven? contained Cellophane and Cyboogie teases, and a Head on Pill jam. Venusian 2 through Sense was released through the Official Bootlegger program as part of Live in Brussels ‘19. Cavs’s drum solo during ‘Open Water’ is featured in the ‘Chunky Shrapnel’ album under the name 'Parking'. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete. All songs besides Doom City have been confirmed via audio/video recordings, and The River is incomplete. Doom City has been confirmed through contemporaneous discussions through various social media. Any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net. Poster By Jason Galea Edition of 400

Doom City was on the written setlist after Billabong Valley but was not played. Wah Wah contained a River intro and The River teases and quotes. Head On/Pill contained a flute solo from Stu, Rattlesnake teases and Alter Me and Am I In Heaven? teases and quotes. Stu’s flute solo from the ‘Head On/Pill’ jam is featured in the ‘Chunky Shrapnel’ album. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete, but only partial recordings are available. Venusian 2, Hot Water, Wah Wah, Road Train, Boogieman Sam and Head On/Pill have been confirmed via audio/video recordings. The remaining songs were confirmed through contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net. Poster By Jason Galea Edition of 200

Evil Star was played through the PA speakers before and as the band came on stage. After Billabong Valley a kid was invited on stage to hug the band. Am I In Heaven? contained teases and quotes of Pill, Boogieman Sam, and Alter Me. Organ Farmer was on the setlist before Am I in Heaven? but wasn't played. This show was released through the Official Bootlegger program as Live in Paris ‘19. Poster by Jason Galea Edition of 200

Head On/Pill contained Rattlesnake quotes, Robot Stop, Venusuan 2 and The River teases and Hot Water, Am I In Heaven, Alter Me, and Cellophane teases and quotes, as well as guest performances from Stonefield and ORB members. Parts of the ‘Head On/Pill’ jam are featured in the ‘Chunky Shrapnel’ album. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist is believed to be complete. Most of Head On/Pill was confirmed by audio/video recording. The remaining songs were confirmed via contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net. Poster By Jason Galea Edition of 100

This show featured the live debuts of Fury, Some of Us, and O.N.E. Nuclear Fusion did not include the vocal intro, though Joey initially indicated that he was going to have Cavs do it. E. Bobby G. and Leah Senior were shouted out after Static Electricity. Pleura was stopped midway through due to sound issues with the band’s monitors and Joey joked that they were going to make a concept album out of the “fart noises” that only they could hear. The song was then resumed from where they left off. Straws in the Wind was dedicated to Hayden Green. Billabong Valley contained Sleep Drifter and Nuclear Fusion teases. Rattlesnake contained Nuclear Fusion teases. The Reticent Raconteur and The Lord of Lightning featured narration by Leah Senior.

Ambrose was introduced as “The Shrimp Man” before Straws in the Wind. Billabong Valley contained Sleep Drifter and Rattlesnake teases. Sleep Drifter contained Honey and Nuclear Fusion teases. This show was released through the Official Bootlegger program as Live in Melbourne '21.

This show featured the live debuts of See Me and The Hungry Wolf of Fate. Sleep Drifter contained Nuclear Fusion teases. Nuclear Fusion did not include the throat singing intro. Prior to Pleura Stu led a call-and-response chant with the audience, leading Joey to ask “Freddie Mercury who?” Pleura was introduced as a song about Blu-ray. The Hungry Wolf of Fate was printed as “The Hungry Wolf of Fire” on the written setlist. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The available recordings of this show are incomplete (Honey missing; Rattlesnake & Straws in the Wind incomplete). The missing songs were confirmed via the written setlist for this show as well as contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations for the missing or incomplete songs that require audio confirmation (segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net.

The Book was played for the first time since 2018-03-07. (135 show gap) D-Day was played for the first time since 2018-03-16. (127 show gap). Melting was played for the first time since 2019-07-06. (60 show gap) KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete, but only partial recordings exist. KGLW.net staff was only able to confirm K.G.L.W. (Intro) through audio or video recordings. Despite the incomplete recordings, KGLW.net staff believes the setlist is complete based on contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that requires audio confirmation (segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net.

This show was part of the 2021 Meadow Music Festival KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete, but no recordings are available. KGLW.net staff believes the setlist is complete based on the written setlist for this show as well as contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net.

This was the Microtonal Night show of the Princess Theatre residency, the third of five planned shows, each featuring a different specific genre and preannounced songs. The Book featured a drum solo by Cavs. Doom City was introduced as a song about planet Earth. Billabong Valley featured guest vocals by Grace Cummings. Rattlesnake contained teases of Sleep Drifter, Honey, O.N.E., Nuclear Fusion and Billabong Valley. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete, but only partial recordings exist. Recordings of K.G.L.W. (Intro) and Automation are unavailable and several other songs are incomplete. The missing songs were confirmed based on the preannounced song lists for each of the 5 planned genre specific shows and contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net. Poster By Jason Galea Edition of 200
Hell was introduced as a song about L.A.  Automation was introduced as a song about the near-term future.

3 hour marathon set. Before the show, "Timeland" was played on the speakers. The intro to Nuclear Fusion was done by the band's sound tech Gaspard. Mr. Beat contained a Persistence tease. Billabong Valley contained a Sleep Drifter tease. During the setbreak, "Smoke & Mirrors" was also played via the venue's speakers. I'm Not In Your Mind contained a Dripping Tap tease. Gaia featured a drum solo. Cellophane featured Stu on flute. The River was dedicated to "Ambrose's ass" and the second segment was played faster per Stu's request. Work This Time featured a guitar solo. Before The Dripping Tap, Stu shouted out the band's crew. The Dripping Tap contained Iron Lung quotes. Mystery Jack was on the setlist after The River, but not played due to time constraints. 

Poster By Jake Foreman

Superbug (lyric changed from “H1N1” to “Coronavirus” referencing COVID-19). Inner Cell was dedicated to the former Australian Prime Minister Scott Morrison, who had lost an election that day. Inner Cell was played for the first time since 2019-10-15 (54 show gap), and Loyalty and Horology were played for the first time since 2019-10-18 (52 show gap). Cut Throat Boogie featured Boogieman Sam teases and quotes, Change teases, “Got My Mojo Working” (Ann Cole) quotes, and “My Babe” (Little Walter) quotes. Persistence featured Change teases and Horology teases. Am I in Heaven? featured Cut Throat Boogie, Hot Water, and Change teases and The Dripping Tap, Iron Lung, Cellophane, Persistence, Sea of Trees, Magenta Mountain, and Ice V teases and quotes. The Lord of Lightning was on the printed setlist after Magenta Mountain but was not played.
data.soundcheck: (possibly incomplete) Inner Cell, Loyalty, Magenta Mountain, Mars for the Rich

data.shownotes: This was the first of five nights in Barcelona for Primavera Sound. Honey contained Sleep Drifter and Rattlesnake teases. The printed setlist contained a different song order - 'Self-Immolate' first and 'Mars for the Rich' second. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete. Gaia through Honey, Magenta Mountain, and The Dripping Tap have been confirmed via audio/video recordings. The remaining songs were confirmed via the physical written setlist and contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net.

Raining Blood (Slayer) played before and as the band came on stage. The River [1] contained Wah Wah teases and parts I, II, & III were played before transitioning to Wah Wah, which contained The River teases and quotes. Part IV of the The River was played after Road Train. Ambergris was introduced as having slap bass. After Ambergris, Joey shouts out opener Grace Cummings. Slow Jam 1 contained an Iron Lung vocal jam and Witchcraft teases. Ataraxia was introduced as "Tanaraxia", which was explained to be a song about Joey wanting to be tan. Sleep Drifter contained a Doom City and Billabong Valley tease. Float Along – Fill Your Lungs contained a metal jam. Poster by Bjenny Montero Edition of 100

Sleep Drifter contained Honey quotes and teases and O.N.E., Billabong Valley, and Rattlesnake teases. Ambrose quoted “Fuck tha Police” (N.W.A) in Billabong Valley. Gaia featured a Cavs drum solo. Leah Senior was shouted out before Magma. Poster by Jason Galea 220 Standard / 30 Foil

Her and I contained Hell's Itch teases.  After The Fourth Colour, Joey asks the crowd to “take a step back”. The Grim Reaper contained Sadie Sorceress quotes. Alter Me III and Altered Beast IV were performed with Leah Senior providing the narration. Alter Me III and Altered Beast IV were played for the first time since 2019-10-08 (96 show gap). Evil Death Roll contained Alter Me teases, Hell's Itch teases and a Hypertension Jam, which would debut properly the following night.

Poster By Arash Zarifian
Standard 250 / 30 Foil Prints

Evil Death Roll did not include the Invisible Face section and instead featured a Hypertension-esque jam (see below). The intro to Ambergris featured musical banter regarding a “big-ass beer”. Leah Senior was shouted out prior to Crumbling Castle. KGLW.net Staff Notes: There was a good deal of discussion about whether the jam in Evil Death Roll constituted a Hypertension tease or was merely suggesting a variation on Hypertension through Stu’s playing. We decided that this example did not qualify as a “tease”, “quote”, or full “jam.” Rather than expand our lexicon to include “motif” or “theme,” we opted to simply mention and qualify it in the setlist notes. Poster By Jordan Speer

Vomit Coffin featured the now-infamous “Amby Snot Rocket”. Blame It on the Weather was humorously announced as the “complete opposite style of music” to the show-opening Murder of the Universe suite. Work This Time featured a guitar solo. Cut Throat Boogie was announced as a song about Ambrose getting stabbed in the neck with a broken bottle. Wah Wah began with the intro to The River and subsequently featured The River quotes and teases, as well as a jam. Sadie Sorceress featured an additional verse from The Grim Reaper played over the music to Sadie Sorceress. Joey requested the cameraperson zoom in to his face as close as possible during the intro to Self-Immolate and introduced Cavs as “John Henry Bonham”, followed by a drum solo and a “Moby Dick” (Led Zeppelin) tease, plus an additional brief drum solo and “Moby Dick” tease at the end of the song. Before Her and I (Slow Jam 2), the weather was discussed and the band’s ignorance regarding Fahrenheit to Celsius conversions was revealed. The song itself featured a Flamethrower jam, Slow Jam 1 and Magma teases, and a brief Cut Throat Boogie jam. Hot Wax was dedicated to one of the band's sound engineers, Joe Santarpia. Timeland was played over the PA as the setbreak music. Head On/Pill opened with “The Star-Spangled Banner” intro, contained Hypertension teases and a Witchcraft tease, and was unfinished leading into Am I in Heaven?. Venusian 1 closed with a Cavs drum solo which led into Venusian 2. Ambrose introduced Billabong Valley as being about a bushranger and is interrupted by Joey calling him “mad-cunt Morgan”. Let Me Mend The Past, which contained an It Ain't Me, Babe (Bob Dylan) quote, was announced as a song about Ambrose’s somewhat troubled upbringing and was dedicated to Edith, Ambrose’s sister. Alter Me III and Altered Beast IV were performed with Leah Senior providing the narration. Float Along - Fill Your Lungs contained a metal jam. Tetrachromacy and Hypertension were on the printed setlist but cut due to time constraints. This show was released through the Official Bootlegger program as part of Live at Red Rocks ‘22. Poster By Jason Galea Second Edition of Poster

This show featured the debut of Gila Monster. Honey contained Billabong Valley, Automation, and Rattlesnake teases. Iron Lung contained Hypertension teases. The River contained Wah Wah teases. Self-Immolate contained a “Fire” (Jimi Hendrix) quote and featured a drum solo by Cavs with “Machine Gun” (Jimi Hendrix) teases. After an instrumental intro to Am I in Heaven?, Stu, Joey, and Amby discuss recent dreams before continuing with the song. The song itself contained a “Stairway to Heaven” (Led Zeppelin) quote as well as “Stiff Upper Lip” (AC/DC) and Rattlesnake teases. Poster By Drew Millward

Evil Death Roll was introduced as a song about crocodiles and contained The Dripping Tap and Trapdoor teases.  Alter Me I contained Ice V teases.  Billabong Valley and Honey contained Sleep Drifter teases.  Ambrose quoted Polygondwanaland before Inner Cell. The Grim Reaper contained Torture Chamber quotes and an extra verse from Sadie Sorceress.  Los Bitchos joined the band for Trapdoor, which contained a percussion solo.

Poster by Lewy Jones

This show featured the debut of Astroturf. Following the Mind Fuzz suite Amby quoted “Runnin’ With the Devil” (Van Halen). Magenta Mountain had lyrics changed to “I don’t believe Stu, his eyes deceive you.” Magenta Mountain contained a tease of The Grim Reaper. The Grim Reaper contained Torture Chamber quotes and featured an additional verse from Sadie Sorceress. Shanghai was on the printed setlist following The Grim Reaper and was attempted but not played due to technical difficulties. Ice V contained a Blindness (The Fall) jam. Poster By Jason Galea 215 Standard / 80 Foil Print

Self-Immolate featured a drum solo by Cavs.  This Thing contained teases & quotes of The Dripping Tap.

Poster By Mathias Krebser
160 Standard Print

The Grim Reaper featured “I’m the Shrimp Reaper” vocals and contained quotes of Torture Chamber, Sadie Sorceress, "Intergalactic” (Beastie Boys) and “One, Two, Freddy’s Coming For You” (A Nightmare on Elm Street) with lyrics changed to “Shrimpy’s coming for you.” Static Electricity was introduced as a song about the time Stu almost got electrocuted in Thailand. O.N.E. contained Straws In The Wind teases. Boogieman Sam contained Rattlesnake quotes, The Bitter Boogie teases and quotes; “La Grange” (ZZ Top) teases and quotes, “Going Up the Country” (Canned Heat) quotes, The Dripping Tap teases, “Whole Lotta Rosie” (AC/DC) teases and “Tutti Frutti” (Little Richard) quotes. The Dripping Tap contained Hell's Itch teases and a Witchcraft jam. Poster By Job van Rijen

Boogieman Sam contained Daily Blues quotes. The Dripping Tap was dedicated to Cavs' dad who lives in Deniliquin and is an "amazing plumber." Prior to Willoughby’s Beach, which was played for the first time since 2022-04-18 (122 show gap), the band mentions they had to bring their amps from home. Joey mentions his replacement amp makes him sound like he's in The Vines and teased the intro to “Can't Stop” (Red Hot Chili Peppers). Gaia featured a Motor Spirit jam and a drum solo by Cavs. Slow Jam 1 was on the written setlist after Iron Lung and Rattlesnake was on the written setlist after Billabong Valley, but they were not performed.

This show featured the debut of Le Risque, which featured vocals from Cavs, making it his vocal debut. Grace Cummings unfortunately had to cancel at short notice, and was replaced with local Austrian band, Hypnotic Floor. Venusian 2 was introduced as a song about Venus. Slow Jam 1 contained Ice V, Sad Pilot, and Loyalty teases and a Chang'e (Extended) jam with lyrics. O.N.E. contained a Straws In The Wind intro. Billabong Valley was performed without Ambrose on guitar, but Stu on guitar for the second half and contained a Minimum Brain Size and Doom City tease. The banter between Billabong Valley and Le Risqué contained quotes and teases of My Generation by Limp Bizkit. Garden Goblin was introduced as being called Borat after Cookie’s vocals on the song. Iron Lung was dedicated to John Frusciante and contained Murder of The Universe, Witchcraft, and Hypertension teases. Hypertension contained a Robot Stop intro and teases of the new song and Evil Death Roll. Evil Death Roll did not contain the Invisible face segment and had Witchcraft, Converge, and Crumbling Castle teases. After the show, Ambrose sang “so long, farewell” from The sound of Music Poster by Amy Jean; Edition of 100

Gondii contained Extinction quotes and The Grim Reaper quotes and teases. A segue into The Grim Reaper out of Gondii was attempted but scrapped, and led to The Grim Reaper being skipped. Before Evil Death Roll, Stu teased Voodoo Child (Slight Return) and Little Wing (both by Jimi Hendrix). Joey yelled Free Palestine in Pleura. Poster by Amy Jean; Edition of 100

The entire band sat in with Grace Cummings for her song "Heaven". Joey thanked Grace before the show started, and Stu mentioned that they let the crew write the setlist. Before Danger $$$, Stu mentioned Gaspard requested the song. Wah Wah contained a The River intro. Only Part I, II, and III of The River was performed and they contained Wah Wah quotes with the "wah wah" refrain changed to "boogie boogie". Road Train was requested by Andrea. Mirage City was played for Jason Galea and was played electric for the first time. Before Sad Pilot, they dedicated the song to Sammy and talked about him recording and playing pedal steel on the new album. Work This Time was dedicated to Grace Cummings. The Dripping Tap was played for Maclay Heriot and contained a Motor Spirit jam, The Silver Cord teases, and Sea of Trees teases. The intro jam to Sleep Drifter contained O.N.E, Sleep Drifter, and Honey teases. Honey contained O.N.E, If Not Now, Then When?, and Billabong Valley teases. Ambrose quoted Ain’t No Mountain High Enough (Marvin Gaye & Tammi Terrell) before Billabong Valley. Before Motor Spirit, Stu asked the crowd who was throwing dinosaurs on stage, and Ambrose quoted Deserted Dunes Welcome Weary Feet. Motor Spirit was played for Jess Lewis because "it sounds like Tool". After Dragon, the band discussed playing Am I In Heaven? but pivoted to Self-Immolate.

data.jamchart_notes: Performing the first verse from an inflatable gator raft held up by the crowd, Ambrose delivers impassioned vocals throughout the song. Colorful guitar work winds into Billabong’s iconic slow-down section where, after Stu takes a quick restroom break, the band stick the landing. The first of the “Amby wander” Billabong Valley’s that became a definitive staple of the 2024 NA tour.
data.shownotes:
Hot Water contained Robot Stop, Am I In Heaven?, and The Dripping Tap teases. Robot Stop, which was incomplete, contained Ice V, Daily Blues, and Am I In Heaven? teases and Field of Vision quotes. The second Hot Water contained a chant of "New York City". Ice V contained a "Blindness" (The Fall) jam and improvised lyrics. The Bitter Boogie contained the drums from Muddy Water and Ice V teases. You Can Be Your Silhouette was introduced as a song about being who you want to be. Hot Wax contained You Can Be Your Silhouette teases. Converge was introduced as a song about storms before Planet B, as Stu confused them on the setlist. The Great Chain of Being contained an "On The Road Again" (Canned Heat) tease. Motor Spirit was dedicated to Cavs "because it's about cars" and contained a You Can Be Your Silhouette and Robot Stop tease. Slow Jam 1 contained Crumbling Castle, Sad Pilot and Ice V teases. Billabong Valley was preceded by a "Microtonal Jazz Jam" with Stu referencing Sexy Alien and Joey singing The Star Spangled Banner. In the song itself, Ambrose crowdsurfed on an inflatable gator and quoted Should I Stay Or Should I Go (The Clash). Following Automation, Joey shouted out opener Geese. A crowd member then told the band to play Fishing For Fishies and the full band (besides Cavs) teased it. The band then started to name classic rock songs and teased Stairway To Heaven and Moby Dick (both Led Zeppelin), and Smoke On the Water (Deep Purple). Stu also shouted out Australian band Cold Chisel. Han-Tyumi, The Confused Cyborg contained a Hypertension tease. Am I In Heaven? contained Evil Death Roll, and Converge teases and Hot Water teases and quotes. Sad Pilot was on the printed setlist but was skipped.

Poster by Jason Galea
Standard Edition of 1200
Holographic Edition of 300

Before Theia, Ambrose quoted Fried. The song itself contained Motor Spirit quotes, a The River jam with Wah Wah quotes, and Motor Spirit and The Silver Cord jams with lyrics. Joey did Michael Jackson-style vocal improv in the intro to Ambergris, which was introduced as a song about sperm whales and contained a short drum solo. Joey did an impression of Guy Fieri before Rats In The Sky. Cavs teased Rock and Roll (Led Zeppelin) before Sad Pilot. After Rats in the Sky, the band heckled Jason Galea to join on tambourine. Before Flight b741, the band got Cavs to hit the gong on his kit. After Flight b741, the band explained that Geelong, aka G-troit, is the sister city to Detroit, as both had a Ford production factory, which closed and destroyed the town. Joey teased Purple Haze (Jimi Hendrix) and Cavs teased Rock and Roll again. You Can Be Your Silhouette contained an extended intro where the band talked about how their talkback mics work and jazz notes. During the song itself, which contained a The End (The Doors) quote, it was described as a song about being yourself. During the intro to Straws In The Wind, the band joked about Ambrose swimming over to Canada and Ambrose walked up to the lights and sound booth.  Nuclear Fusion featured Vincent, a kid from the audience on the intro. Following the intro, Joey teased Twist (Korn). After Nuclear Fusion, Stu shouted out the stream crew. Honey contained O.N.E teases. Minimum Brain Size was introduced as a song about "loser hypermasculine people."  Prior to Rattlesnake Joey conducted a Q&A session with crowd members and Sam. Prior to Billabong Valley, Cavs ran offstage. During Billabong Valley, Joey said he can do a Limp Bizkit beat cause he doesn’t have an electric guitar and doesn’t want to take it to the [Dave] Matthews Bridge, followed by Ambrose climbing on top of the equipment truck on the side of the venue, leading to the line “I’m on the truck!” Her and I (Slow Jam 2), which was last played 2023-06-18 (50 show gap), contained a Slow Jam 1 intro as well as Iron Lung teases.

Poster by Jason Galea
Standard Edition - 600
Foil Edition- 200

The Dripping Tap had a lyric changed to "Times of our Milwaukee" and a Le Risque quote. Hot Water contained teases of Am I In Heaven? and The Dripping Tap. God Is Calling Me Back Home was last played 2015-06-12. (580 show gap) Before The Garden Goblin, the band congratulated Cookie on the Pipe-eye single that released the night before. Magenta Mountain contained a Crumbling Castle tease. Chang'e contained Magenta Mountain teases and quotes and Witchcraft quotes. Extinction contained Magenta Mountain quotes. Billabong Valley contained Sleep Drifter teases. The intro to Honey contained Sleep Drifter teases.

Poster By Job van Rijen
Standard: 500
Gold Foil: 150

Anoxia was last played 2023-08-16. (57 show gap) The beginning of Billabong Valley contained Cotton-Eyed Joe (Traditional) quotes and an Automation tease. Tetrachromacy was last played 2022-10-14 (119 show gap). It's Got Old was last played 2023-06-04 (73 show gap). Before Mystery Jack, Zebra (John Butler) was teased. Dirt was last played 2022-04-13 (169 show gap), and contained a Hot Water tease. Following the Mirage City Reprise, the band teased and quoted We Will Rock You (Queen) with the lyrics changed to "We will Red Rock you". Field of Vision was dedicated to tour manager Jess Lewis. Tetrachromacy through Work This Time featured Joey on acoustic guitar. Rats In The Sky contained a Hot Water tease. Hot Water contained Nutbush City Limits (Ike & Tina Turner), Antarctica, Motor Spirit, and Iron Lung quotes, and Hell's Riff. Ambrose quoted If You Want My Love (Cheap Trick) as the band left the stage. Following the show those attending both the early and late shows were allowed to stay in the venue and Pipe-eye's upcoming album Pipe-defy and Heavy Moss' upcoming album Dead Slow were played over the PA.

Poster by Jason Galea
Standard - 1200
Gold Foil - 300

This show featured the debut of Intrasport, which featured Lucas on Joey's microtonal guitar and Joey on tambourine. Following Billabong Valley Joey shouted out King Stingray and their relationship to Yothu Yindi and Warumpi Band. Hypertension contained teases of Whole Lotta Rosie (AC/DC), La Grange (ZZ Top) and Ice V. Stu teased La Grange again before Antarctica. Joey shouted out Cookie's new Pipe-Eye album in the intro to Ambergris. A segue from Sad Pilot into Rats In the Sky was completed; immediately following the segue the show was stopped for approximately 4 minutes to help a fan who passed out and Rats was then restarted from the beginning. Gaia featured a drum solo by Cavs.

Hypertension contained La Grange (ZZ Top) teases. Joey introduced Cavs as "Michelle Caviar" before Le Risque.  Evil Death Roll contained Mirage City and Hypertension teases. Float Along - Fill Your Lungs contained a Dragon jam with lyrics.

Hot Water featured Ambrose on sax. Raw Feel contained a Muddy Water tease and was unfinished. Muddy Water featured Ambrose on sax and contained The Bitter Boogie teases. The Bitter Boogie also featured Ambrose on sax and contained Muddy Water teases as well as an outro jam with lyrics. Gilgamesh contained Magenta Mountain teases and quotes and was unfinished. Before Billabong Valley Ambrose quoted Hits From the Bong (Cypress Hill).  The Great Chain of Being contained The Bitter Boogie teases.
data.venuename: Plaza Mayor de El Poble Espanyol

data.shownotes: Am I In Heaven? contained Antarctica and Hypertension teases. Self-Immolate featured a drum solo. Dragon featured a fan named Ignas on Stu’s guitar instead of Stu. After Dragon, Joey wished Stu a happy Pink Soup Day (a local festival in Vilnius about beet soup). Billabong Valley contained a See Me quote. Stu said "Fuck Putin" during Pleura. Le Risque was introduced as being called "Pink Soup", to which the band started chanting "Pink Soup", and Joey vocally teased Kernkraft 400 (Zombie Nation). The song itself featured a fan dressed as Evel Knievel on stage during Ambrose's verse, who Stu thanked after the song. Down The Sink was played for the first time since 2023-08-30 (76 show gap), in a new alternate synthpop arrangement, and contained Gilgamesh quotes. As Gilgamesh ended, Joey compared the band's synth playing at the end of the jam to Rammstein. Joey and Cavs teased Blind (Korn) before Trapdoor. The Dripping Tap featured Stu telling a story about him and Joey getting pink soup and how it was the best thing they had ever eaten, with Joey playing his guitar with his teeth because he "spilled pink soup on it", and contained a Tool jam featuring elements and variations of Forty Six & 2 and Schism with Motor Spirit quotes. After The Dripping Tap, Joey said "Free Palestine," "Glory to Ukraine" (from a sign in the audience) and "humanity."

data.jamchart_notes: A somewhat unique rendition in that the band goes into a seemingly non-microtonal jam directly in the middle of a microtonal song.
data.shownotes: The band dressed in drag for the third annual drag night. Theia, Sad Pilot, Most Of What I Like, and Aerodynamic were performed acoustic. Theia contained The River and The Land Before Timeland teases. Most Of What I Like contained Praise You (Fatboy Slim) teases and was dedicated by Joey to his wife Edith. Aerodynamic was played for the first time without an orchestra. Before Venusian 1, the band said if they should have soundchecked it and joked that if they messed it up, they would play Stoned Mullet instead. Following Venusian 1, Joey quoted Chop Suey (System of a Down) and Lucas shouted out festival act Yvie Oddly. Her and I (Slow Jam 2) contained You Can Be Your Silhouette, Am I In Heaven?, The River, Blindness (The Fall), Crumbling Castle, and Monkey Disco (Babe Rainbow) teases. Following Her and I, the band announced that the festival would be played again next year, and shouted out their manager Michelle Cable and the fans at the festival. O.N.E. was introduced as Duran Duran's favorite song. Before Billabong Valley, Joey mentioned Australian rapper RAED. During The Silver Cord, Stu vamped on the lyrics "let's get fucked up" and "everybody wants to save us." Following Daily Blues, Ambrose quoted Scarface (Push It to the Limit) (Paul Engemann). Float Along - Fill Your Lungs was dedicated to Matt Gawiak, a fan that passed away during the show night 1 of the festival and contained a Dragon jam. Ambrose led the crowd in a chant of 'Matt' following Float Along - Fill Your Lungs. The Dripping Tap was also dedicated to Matt Gawaik. Rats In The sky was on the printed setlist after The Garden Goblin but was skipped.

Joey said "Fuck Peter Dutton" during the intro of Pleura. Before Magma Joey shouted "Light 'em up, T!" then said that he's always wanted to say that in Australia. Field of Vision contained a quote of Wipeout (The Surfaris).  Dirt was played for the first time since 2024-11-16 (50 show gap) and was played all electric for the first time. During The Dripping Tap, which contained Magma, Machine Gun (Jimi Hendrix) and Cellophane teases, Stu’s amp broke so Joey told a story while another amp was brought out. After Witchcraft, Cavs performed a drum solo while the rest of the band took a break, followed by Cavs taking his own break. The Mind Fuzz suite was introduced as a song by Jimi Hendrix called I'm In Your Mind Fuzz.  I'm Not In Your Mind contained Trapdoor, Machine Gun (Jimi Hendrix) and The Dripping Tap teases.
